make_pdf("04_research_paper.pdf", "Machine Learning Approaches for Predictive Maintenance", [
    ("Abstract", "This paper presents a comparative study of machine learning algorithms for predictive maintenance in manufacturing environments. We evaluate Random Forest, LSTM networks, and Transformer-based models on a dataset of 50,000 sensor readings from 200 industrial machines over 24 months. Our results show that the Transformer-based approach achieves 94.2% accuracy in predicting failures 48 hours in advance, outperforming LSTM (91.7%) and Random Forest (87.3%)."),
    ("1. Introduction", "Predictive maintenance aims to predict equipment failures before they occur, reducing downtime and maintenance costs. Traditional approaches rely on scheduled maintenance intervals, which often result in either premature replacement of functional components or unexpected failures. Machine learning offers the potential to analyze sensor data patterns and predict failures with high accuracy. The global predictive maintenance market is expected to reach $23.5 billion by 2027."),
    ("2. Methodology", "We collected vibration, temperature, pressure, and acoustic data from 200 CNC machines in three manufacturing plants. Data was sampled at 1Hz for 24 months, yielding approximately 50,000 labeled data points. Features were extracted using a sliding window of 60 minutes with 50% overlap. We used 70% of the data for training, 15% for validation, and 15% for testing. All models were trained on NVIDIA A100 GPUs using PyTorch 2.0."),
    ("3. Results", "The Transformer model achieved the highest F1 score of 0.932, with precision of 0.941 and recall of 0.923. False positive rate was 3.2%, meaning only 3.2% of predicted failures did not actually occur. The model successfully predicted 92.3% of actual failures at least 48 hours in advance. Training time was 4.5 hours for the Transformer model compared to 1.2 hours for LSTM and 0.3 hours for Random Forest."),
    ("4. Discussion", "The Transformer model's superior performance is attributed to its self-attention mechanism, which captures long-range dependencies in sensor data. However, it requires significantly more computational resources for both training and inference. For resource-constrained environments, the LSTM model offers a good balance between accuracy and computational cost. Random Forest remains viable for scenarios where interpretability is prioritized over raw accuracy."),
    ("5. Conclusion", "We demonstrate that Transformer-based models achieve state-of-the-art performance for predictive maintenance. Future work will explore federated learning approaches to train models across multiple manufacturing sites without sharing raw sensor data. We also plan to investigate the use of foundation models pre-trained on industrial sensor data."),
])
 
